and plaged with this vnnaturall deuision. All the other discordes, sectes
and faccions almoste liuely florishe and continue at this presente
tyme, to the greate displesure and preiudice of all the christian publike
welth. But the olde deuided controuersie betwene the fornamed families
of Lācastre and Yorke, by the vnion of Matrimony celebrate and
consummate betwene the high and mighty Prince Kyng Henry the
seuenth and the lady Elizabeth his moste worthy Quene, the one beeyng
indubitate heire of the hous of Lancastre, and the other of Yorke
was suspended and appalled in the person of their moste noble 
