hym with all, but it was the cause of his and their discomforte: for
he poured in so muche, that when he came into the place in Smithfelde,
where he should fight, bothe his witte and strength failed hym: and so
he beyng a tall and a hardye personage, ouerladed with hote drynkes,
was vanqueshed of his seruaunte, beyng but a cowarde and a wretche,
whose body was drawen to Tiborne, &amp; there hanged and behedded. In
