                  AFTER this commocion, the kyng hymself came into Kent, &amp; there
sat in iudgement vpō the offendors, and if he had not mitigated his iustice,
with mercie and compassion, more then fiue .C. by the rigor of his
lawe, had been iustely put to execucion: but he cōsidered, bothe their fragilitie
and innocencie, and how thei with peruerse people, were seduced
and deceiued: and so punished the stubburne heddes, and deliuered the
ignorāt &amp; miserable people, to the greate reioysyng of all his subiectes.
               
