fast as coulde be possible the Easterlyuges, whiche had many shippes
of warre on the sea, hym espied (accordyng to the olde prouerbe) one yll
commeth neuer alone, and with .vii. or .viii. gallant shyppes, began to
chace the kyng &amp; his cōpany. The kynges shyp was good with sayle, &amp;
so much gat of the Easterlinges, that she came on the coast of Holland,
and so discended lower, before a towne in Holland, called Alquemare,
and there cast Ancker as nere the towne as was possible, because
they coulde not enter the Hauen at an ebbyng water. The Easterlynges
also approched the Englishe shippe as nere as their great shyppes
coulde come at the lowe water, entendynge at the fludde to haue obteyned
their pray, and so they were likely to do, if Monsieur de Gronture,
gouernour for duke Charles in Holland had not at that season bene
personally present in those parties.
