The lordes whom he knewe at variaunce, he in his deathe bedde (as he
thought) brought too good concorde, loue and amitee. And a litle before
his deathe, he had left gatheryng of money of his subiectes, which is the
onely thyng that draweth the hartes of Englishe menne from their kinges
and princes: nor nothyng he either enterprised nor tooke in hande,
by the whiche he shoulde bee driuen there vnto. For his tribute out of
