feare, and not willyng nor daryng come abrode, but to lye as prisoners

in a dongeon, wrote to the Kyng to come thether in persone, and to haue
the honor of so high an entreprise: whiche writyng the Kynges counsaill
nothyng allowed, for puttyng the kyng in ieoperdy vpon the chaunce of
the sea. Wherefore the kyng wrote sharply to hym, to accomplishe that
whiche apperteined to his duetie: whiche caused hym to take courage
and put thynges in aduenture as after you shall here.
            
            
