bothe nigh and far, wer many of the Frenche gard, ridyng and beholdyng
the maner of the Englishe parte, some of the kynges gard, and
some of the duke of Burbons gard, and some of the Admirall of Fraū
                  ces
Gard, whiche slily marked the conueighaunce of the people of Englande.
At the houre of metyng appoynted, the Lordes of Englande set
their people and seruauntes in good arraie of battaill, in a plain felde
directly before the castle of Guysnes. The kyng of Englande commaū
                  ded
that his Garde should bee set in the breste of the battaill, or bend of
footemen, and so it was doen. This battaill of footemen conducted thē
                  selfes
so in ordre, that from the firste to the laste, neuer a persone of the
