and led him through the citie, who desired euer the people to pray for
him, of whom some wept and lamented, and sayd, this is thende of euil

life. God forgeue him, he was a proude prince, It is pitie that he behaued
him so against his kyng and liege lorde, whō God preserue. Thus
aboute .iiii. of the clocke he was brought as a cast man to the Tower.
               Frydaie the .xvii. day of Maie, about .xi. of the clocke. This duke we
a great power was deliuered to Ihon Kyeme and Ihon Skeuyngton
shyriffes, who led him to the skaffolde on Tower hill, where he sayd he
had offended the kynges grace through negligence and lacke of grace,
and desired al noblemen to beware by him, and al men to pray for him,
and that he trusted to dye the kynges true man. Thus mekely with an
a
