customes were greater now, then thei were before tyme: also he alleged
sumpteous buildynges, plate, riche apparell, of menne, women, children,
and seruauntes, fatte feastes, and dilicate dishes, whiche thynges
were all tokens of greate aboundance: with whiche repetyng of mennes
substaunce, as though he had repined or disdained, that any man should
fare well, or be well clothed, but hymself, the commons greatly grudged.
And when he was departed out of the house, it was proued, that honest
apparell of the commodities of this Realme, aboundance of plate, and
honest viandes, were profitable to the realme, and not prodigall.
               After long debatyng, the Commons concluded to graunte .ii.s. of the
pound, of euery mannes landes or goodes, that was worth .xx. pounde,
or might dispende .xx. pounde, to be taken for the kyng, and so vpwarde
of euery .xx.s. twoo .s. and from .xl.s. to .xx. pounde, of euery .xx.s.xii.d.
and vnder .xl.s. of euery hed, xvi. yeres and vpward .iiii.d. to bee paied
in two yeres. This graunt was reported to the Cardinall, whiche therwith
was sore discontent, and saied, that the lordes had graunted .iii.s.

of the pound, whiche was proued vntrue, for in dede thei had graunted
nothyng, but harkened all vpon the commons.
