wherefore when thei had dronke well, thei spake largely, and
bosted how thei had victailed the English armies, and found them cartes
and cariages, and thought it not kyndly doen, to refuse them as old
frendes &amp; make peace wyth old enemies, but thei did not considre what
money the Englishemen left in their countrey, nor how the Frenchmen
for dred of the Englishemen, would not inuade Flaunders, so that thei
lyued quietly, all this thei considered not.
