               After that the Frenche kyng was deliuered, and the peace concluded,
the Emperor was fully determined to passe the seas into Italy, and so
to Rome, and there to be crouned Emperor, wherof hearyng the bishop
of Rome, called Pope Clement the seuenth, a man of great wit and vice,
and of litle vertue or learnyng: much doubted in hymself what damage
might come to hym, if the emperor had bothe Naples, Scicill, and the
Duchie of Millain, and also wer crouned Emperor. Wherefore he sent
to the Uenicians, and to the Florētines, and to Fraunces Sforce duke
of Millain, whiche had committed treason against themperor, and was
depriued by iudgeme
