                     ion of the Cardinal. He forced litle on symony &amp; was not pityful and stode affeccionate
in his owne opinion: In open presence he would lye and say vntruth
and was double both in speche and meanyng: He would promise
muche and performe lytle: He was vicious of his body and gaue the
clergie euil example: He hated sore the citie of London and feared it: It
