of his body, whiche is the greatest displeasure that maye come
to a Prince: The Mariage was well ment bothe of the kynges father
and the Quenes father, and they maryed together by the aduyce and
councell of their frendes, and so louyngly continued together as man
and wyfe without any scruple or doubte, tyll you of Spayne moued
fyrst the question and put the maryage in ambiguitie, and therfore you
can not with honour thynke but that the Kyng hath doone lyke a wyse
Prince to searche out the solucion of your doubte which so neare toucheth
his soule and the suretye of his Realme: And all thynge that he
hath done he hath done by great aduysement and with a great deliberacion,
wherefore no reasonable man can saye but he hath done lyke a
wyse and vertuous Prince. The Marques hearynge this aunswere
